column1: Great Britain
The United Kingdom (or Great Britain) is situated on the British Isles. The British Isles consist of two large islands
column2: Great Britain and Ireland
column3: and about five thousand small islands. Their total area is over 244
column4: 000 square kilometres.

column1: The United Kingdom is made up of four countries: England
column2: Wales
column3: Scotland (on the island of Great Britain)
column4: and Northern Ireland (on the island of Ireland). Their capitals are London
column5: Cardiff
column6: Edinburgh
column7: and Belfast respectively. The capital of the UK is London.

column1: The British Isles are separated from the European continent by the North Sea and the English Channel. The western coast of Great Britain is washed by the Atlantic Ocean and the Irish Sea.
The surface of the British Isles varies very much. The north of Scotland is mountainous and is called the Highlands
column2: while the south
column3: which has beautiful valleys and plains
column4: is called the Lowlands. The north and west of England are mountainous
column5: but all the rest โ east
column6: centre
column7: and south-east โ is a vast plain. Mountains are not very high. Ben Nevis in Scotland is the highest mountain (1

column1: There are a lot of rivers in Great Britain
column2: but they are not very long. The Severn is the longest river
column3: while the Thames is the deepest one.

column1: The mountains
column2: the Atlantic Ocean
column3: and the warm waters of Gulf Stream influence on the climate of the British Isles. It is mild the whole year round.

column1: The UK is one of the world's smallest countries. Its population is over 57 million. About 80 % of the population is urban.
The UK is a highly developed industrial country. It is known as one of the world's largest producers and exporters of machineryยป electronics
column2: textile
column3: aircraft
column4: and navigation equipment. One of the chief industries of the country is shipbuilding.

column1: The UK is a constitutional monarchy. In law
column2: Head of the State is Queen. In practice
column3: Queen reigns
column4: but does not rule. The country is ruled by the elected government with the Prime Minister at the head. The British Parliament consists of two chambers: the House of Lords and the House of Commons.

column1: There are three main political parties in Great Britain: the Labour
column2: the Conservative
column3: and the Liberal parties.

column1: London
London is the capital of Great Britain
column2: its political
column3: economic and cultural centre. It's one of the largest cities in the world. Its population is more than million people. London is situated on the river Thames. The city is very old and beautiful. It was founded more than two thousand years ago. Traditionally London is divided into several parts: the City
column4: the West End
column5: the East End and Westminster. The City is the oldest part of London
column6: its financial and business centre. The heart of the City is the Stock Exchange. Westminster is the most important part of the capital. It's the administrative centre. The Houses of Parliament
column7: the seat of the British Government
column8: are there. It's a very beautiful building with two towers and a very big clock called Big Ben. Big Ben is really the bell which strikes every quarter of an hour. Opposite the Houses of Parliament is Westminster Abbey. It's a very beautiful church built over 900 years ago. The tombs of many great statesmen
column9: scientists and writers are there.

column1: To the west of Westminster is West End. Here we find most of the big shops
column2: hotels
column3: museums
column4: art galleries
column5: theatres and concert halls. Picadilly Circus is the heart of London's West End. In the West End there are wide streets with beautiful houses and many parks
column6: gardens and squares. To the east of Westminster is the East End
column7: an industrial district of the capital. There are no parks or gardens in the East End and you can't see many fine houses there. Most of the plants and factories are situated there. London has many places of interest. One of them is Buckingham Palace. It's the residence of the Queen. The English are proud of Trafalgar Square
column8: which was named so in memory of the victory at the battle. There in 1805 the English fleet defeated the fleet of France and Spain. The last place of interest I should like to mention
column9: is the British Museum
column10: the biggest museum in London. The museum is famous for its library -one of the richest in the world.

column1: All London's long-past history is told by its streets. There are many streets in London which are known all over the"" world. Among them Oxford Street
column2: Downing Street and a lot of others can be mentioned. And tourists are usually attracted not only by the places of interest but by the streets too. In conclusion I should say if you are lucky enough to find yourself in London some day you will have a lot to see and enjoy there.

column1: Travelling
Millions of people all over the world spend their holidays traveling. They travel to see other continents
column2: modern cities and the ruins of ancient towns
column3: they travel to enjoy picturesque places
column4: or just for a change of scene. It's always interesting to discover new things
column5: different ways of life
column6: to meet different people
column7: to try different food
column8: to listen to different musical rhythms.

column1: Those who live in the country like to go to a big city and spend their time visiting museums and art galleries
column2: looking at shop windows and dining at exotic restaurants. City-dwellers usually like a quiet holiday by the sea or in the mountains
column3: with nothing to do but walk and bathe and laze in the sun.

column1: Most travelers and holiday-makers take a camera with them and take pictures of everything that interests them - the sights of a city
column2: old churches and castles
column3: views of mountains
column4: lakes
column5: valleys
column6: plains
column7: waterfalls
column8: forests; different kinds of trees
column9: flowers and plants
column10: animals and birds. Later
column11: perhaps years later
column12: they will be reminded by the photos of the happy time they have had.

column1: People travel by train
column2: by plane
column3: by boat
column4: by car
column5: by bike and on foot. People travel to have a holidays or to have business. If people have business trips they choose the fastest transport. They often travel by plane or by train. It is very expensive but it is very fast. And if people want to have a rest they choose traveling by boat
column6: by car
column7: on horseback and etc. When you travel by car or by bike you can stop where you want. All means of travel have their advantages and disadvantages. And people choose one according to their plans and destinations.

column1: If we are fond of traveling
column2: we see and learn a lot of things that we can never see or learn at home
column3: though we may read about them in books and newspapers
column4: and see pictures of them on TV. The best way to study geography is to travel
column5: and the best way to get to know and understand people is to meet them in their own homes. The best way to study geography is to travel
column6: and the best way to get to know and understand people is to meet them in their own homes.

column1: Moscow
The capital city of the Russian Federation is Moscow. It is one of the largest cities in the world. More than 18 million people live in Moscow. Moscow is the cultural
column2: communications
column3: government
column4: industrial
column5: scientific
column6: and transportation centre of Russia. It lies in western Russia
column7: in the European part of the country. The Moscow River
column8: for which the city was named
column9: flows through the city.

column1: Moscow was founded during 12th century. Moscow emerged as the most powerful Russian city in the late 1400's. The princes of Moscow played a leading role in uniting various Russian lands and in conquering non-Russian peoples and territories. Moscow became the capital of the Russian Empire and was the home of Russia's czars until 1712
column2: when the capital was moved to St. Petersburg. Moscow again became the Russian capital in 1918
column3: after the Bolsheviks (later called Communists) took control of the country. In 1922
column4: Russia and three other republics united to form the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics. Moscow was chosen as the Soviet capital.

column1: Moscow is built in the shape of a wheel. This shape can be traced to the city's early history
column2: when rings of fortifications were built to protect it from attack. Today
column3: wide boulevards extend from the city's centre
column4: forming the spokes of the wheel. They cross circular boulevards
column5: which make up the inner and outer rims of the wheel. A major highway circles Moscow. Past the highway lies the Green Belt
column6: a ring of forests and parks covering about 1
column7: 800 square kilometres.

column1: The oldest and busiest sections of Moscow lie near the Kremlin
column2: a huge walled fortress at the city's historic centre. Just to the north and east of the Kremlin is the main business
column3: commercial
column4: and administrative district. Encircling this area and the Kremlin are Moscow's main shopping streets and many cultural buildings. Most of the city's new residential and industrial districts lie in the outermost rings.

column1: At the city's heart on the banks of the River Moscow lies the Kremlin
column2: a walled fortress housing all the government buildings. Nearby St. Basil's Cathedral was built in the 16th century to celebrate a military victory; it is now a museum.

column1: Russia

Russia is one of the largest countries of the world. It occupies about one seventh part of dry land. Its total area is over 17 million square kilometres. The country borders Finland and Norway in the north-west and China and Korea in the south-east. Its washed by several seas and three oceans.
There are different types of climate in the various regions of Russia. It is very cold in Yakutia even in summer. Central Russia has mild climate: winters are quite cold
column2: springs and autumns are cool and wet
column3: summers are hot. In Krasnodarsky Region the temperature is above zero all year round
column4: even in winter. Summer is really hot there. In some locations the climate is subtropical. The climate of Siberia is continental: summers are hot and dry and winters are cold and windy. There are a lot of mountains in Russia. The oldest ones and very rich in minerals are the Urals. There are many rivers in Russia
column5: the longest ones are Volga in Europe and Yenisei and Ob in Asia. The deepest lakes are Baikal and Ladoga. Baikal water once was purest in the world. Now environment protection organizations' leaders want it to be restored and kept safe and pure. They demand removing industrial enterprises out of its shore.

column1: Russian Federation is very rich in mineral resources such as oil
column2: natural gas
column3: coal
column4: iron ore
column5: gold and diamonds. Moscow is the capital of our country. It was founded in 1147 by Yuri Dolgoruky. It is a busy commercial and industrial Megapolis and a nice city at the same time. There are a lot of art galleries
column6: theatres
column7: museums and monuments in Moscow. The most famous historical place is Moscow Kremlin
column8: where there is the President resides and works. People of Russia take proud of the Kremlin. There are also a great number of beautiful cities in Russia.

column1: Sports and a healthy way of life
Sport is very important in our life. It is popular among young and old people. Many people do morning exercises
column2: jog in the morning
column3: train themselves in clubs
column4: in different sections and take part in sport competitions. Other people like sports too
column5: but they only watch sports games
column6: listen to sports news. They prefer reading interesting stories about sportsmen. But they don't go in for sports. Physical training is an important subject at school. Pupils have got physical training lessons twice a week. Boys and girls play volley-ball and basket-ball at the lessons. There is a sports ground near our school and school-children go in for sports in the open air. A lot of different competitions are held at schools
column7: a great number of pupils take part in them. All participants try to get good results and become winners.

column1: Sport helps people to keep in good health. If you go in for sports
column2: you have good health and don't catch cold. Children and grown-ups must take care of their health and do morning exercises regularly. There are some popular kinds of sports in our country: football
column3: volley-ball
column4: hockey
column5: gymnastics
column6: skiing
column7: skating. Athletics is one of the most popular kinds of sports. It includes such kinds of sports as running
column8: jumping and others. Everybody may choose the sport he (or she) is interested in. There are summer and winter sports. My favourite sport is swimming. I go to the swimming-pool twice a week. But I prefer to rest by the lake or the river and swim there.

column1: William Shakespeare

William Shakespeare was born in April 1564. His father was a rich citizen whose business was making and selling leather gloves. His mother was the daughter of an important farmer. When he was nineteen
column2: William married Anne. Shakespeare had three children: Susannah
column3: the eldest
column4: then twins - a son
column5: Hamlet
column6: and another girl
column7: Judith. In 1587 Shakespeare went to work in London
column8: leaving Anne and the children at home.

column1: Some years later Shakespeare began to write plays. The parents did not even guess that their son would be such an important figure in English poetry and drama and that his plays would still be acted hundred years later in England and all over the world. By 1592 Shakespeare was an important member of well-known company. In 1599 the famous Globe Theatre was built on the south bank of the river Thames. In that theatre most of his plays were performed. It was a round building with the stage in the center
column2: open to the sky. Shakespeareโs Globe was rather different from modern theatres. The plays were performed in the open air and the audience got wet if it rained. There was no scenery
column3: very few props
column4: and the only lighting was the daylight that came from the open roof above. Women in those days werenโt allowed to act in public and all the parts (even Juliet!) were played by men. Much of the audience stood to watch the performance and moved around
column5: talking with each other and throwing fruit at the stage if they didnโt like something.

column1: By 1603 Shakespeare was the leading poet and dramatist of his time. He continued to write for the next ten years. Shakespeare wrote 37 plays: 10 tragedies (such as Hamlet
column2: King Lear
column3: Othello
column4: Macbeth)
column5: 17 comedies (such as As You Like It
column6: Twelfth Night
column7: Much Ado About Nothing)
column8: 10 historical plays (such as Henry 4
column9: Richard 3). He also left 7 books of poems and sonnets. In 1613 he finally stopped writing and went to live in Stratford where he died in 1616.
